      • unlift

        public static <I,O> PartialFunction<I,O> unlift(Function<? super I,? extends O> function)
        Returns a partial function for the specified function. In spirit, this is the opposite of "lifting" a partial function to a total function. Since partial functions do not support null results, the returned partial function will be undefined for any inputs where the specified function returns null. All other values in the input domain behave as expected and produce a result.
        Parameters:
        function - a function
        Returns:
        a partial function that is defined for all values in the input domain except the ones where the specified function returns null

      • foldRight

        public static <I,O> O foldRight(Iterable<I> values,
                                BiFunction<? super I,? super O,? extends O> function,
                                O seed)
        Performs a fold-right operation over the specified values and returns the result. This operation is recursive and is defined as follows:
          foldr(list, fun, seed) => list.empty?
                            then seed
                            else fun(list.first, foldr(list.rest, fun, seed))
        This results in the following diagram of how elements are composed via the folding function:
               fun
       / \
 list[0]  fun
          / \
    list[1]  fun
             / \
       list[2]  fun
                / \
          list[n]  seed
        That the shape of this tree descends to the right is why this function its named "fold right".
        Parameters:
        values - the values to fold
        function - the reducing function used at each pair-wise fold
        seed - the root value; the result represents this root value, folded into the last element, the result of which is then folded into the next-to-the-last element, etc.
        Returns:
        the result of folding all elements via the given function

      • foldLeft

        public static <I,O> O foldLeft(Iterable<I> values,
                               BiFunction<? super O,? super I,? extends O> function,
                               O seed)
        Performs a fold-left operation over the specified values and returns the result. This operation is recursive and is defined as follows:
          foldl(list, fun, seed) => list.empty?
                            then seed
                            else foldl(list.rest, fun, fun(seed, list.first))
        This results in the following diagram of how elements are composed via the folding function:
                    fun
            / \
          fun  list[n]
          / \
        fun  list[2]
        / \
     fun  list[1]
     / \
 seed  list[0]
        That the shape of this tree descends to the left is why this function its named "fold left".
        Parameters:
        values - the values to fold
        function - the reducing function used at each pair-wise fold
        seed - the root value; the result represents this root value, folded into the first element, the result of which is then folded into the next element, etc.
        Returns:
        the result of folding all elements via the given function
